# MCAT Speedrun UI design direction

When building, redesigning, improving, styling, or polishing any MCAT Speedrun
screen, use a premium, confident, Stripe-inspired product design direction.

Do NOT copy Stripe. Do not use Stripe logos, exact layouts, exact gradients,
exact colors, exact copy, or anything that could be mistaken for Stripe. Use the
broader principles only, adapted originally to this app.

## Product tone
- Calm, high-achiever, trustworthy. This is a tool for serious MCAT students.
- Direct but never degrading. Warnings are gentle and constructive, never alarming.
- Honesty over hype: when the app abstains from a score, the UI should make
  abstention feel responsible and reassuring, not like a failure.

## Visual language
- Strong, deliberate visual hierarchy: one clear primary action per view.
- Clean typography with generous spacing; let content breathe.
- Polished cards and surfaces with soft elevation and consistent radii.
- Beautiful gradients used with restraint, as accents only (e.g. a readiness
  range header), never as loud full-page washes.
- Responsive layouts that hold up from narrow Qt webviews to full windows.

## Evidence-first scoring UI
- Never show a single blended number. Memory, Performance, and Readiness are
  always visually separated.
- Scores are range-first. Show the range prominently, the point estimate
  secondarily, and always attach: confidence, coverage %, last updated, main
  evidence, missing data, and a single best next action.
- Use clear, non-clinical labels for confidence (e.g. Low / Low-medium / Medium
  / High) and consistent color semantics across the app.

## Roadmap and flow
- Roadmap blocks should feel satisfying to complete: clear labels, estimated
  time, section, and mode, with a tactile sense of progress.
- Required vs optional work should be obvious. Optional/free practice is
  encouraged after required work, never punished.

## Implementation conventions
- Reuse existing shared components in `ts/lib/components/` and tokens in
  `ts/lib/sass/` (color palette, root vars, night mode) before adding new ones.
- Support light and dark mode via the existing theme system; never hardcode
  raw colors when a token exists.
- Keep interactions fast and never block the UI; long work shows calm progress.

## Theming tokens to prefer
- Colors via the palette in `ts/lib/sass/_color-palette.scss` and CSS custom
  properties in `_root-vars.scss`.
- Spacing, radius, and elevation via existing Sass helpers/mixins.
